Monte Carlo Simulation for Automation Stocks:

Tesla, Ford, Volkswagen, and Mullen

Group: Sambodhi, Kristina, and Kevin

This is a monte carlo simulation for our stocks for the technical analysis portion of the Valuation project. Data for this simulation is imported from Yahoo Finance.

The following resources are used for reference to build this model: https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/monte-carlo-simulations-for-predicting-stock-prices-python-a64f53585662 https://israeldi.github.io/bookdown/_book/monte-carlo-simulation-of-stock-portfolio-in-r-matlab-and-python.html https://www.kaggle.com/code/prometheus13/a-monte-carlo-simulation-of-stock-prices

Price of stock will be based on the following brownian motion equation:

St=St1erSt=St1er

  • In other words, the price of stock today is based on the price of the stock yesterday and yield of stock for today.
  • We will assume that the stock price is Geometric Brownian Motion process with a drift which will be the general trend and a volatility or randomness component.

Breaking down the equation further we have the following components:

Drift=+122Drift=+122

Volatility=Zscore[RandomVariable(0,1)]Volatility=Zscore[RandomVariable(0,1)]

r=Drift+Volatilityr=Drift+Volatility

Then StSt is calculated as follow:

St=St1e(+122)+Z[Rand(0,1)]St=St1e(+122)+Z[Rand(0,1)]

# Components of the distribution

mu_tesla = np.mean(data['returns'])
print("The mean for",ticker1,"'s daily return distribution is:", mu_tesla, '\n')

sigma_tesla = np.var(data['returns'])

print("The variance for",ticker1,"'s daily return distribution is:", sigma_tesla, '\n')

#Drift for Stock Price
drift_tesla = mu_tesla + (.5*sigma_tesla)
print("The drift for",ticker1,"'s daily return distribution is:", drift_tesla, '\n')

The mean for TSLA 's daily return distribution is: 0.0019166296364038615 

The variance for TSLA 's daily return distribution is: 0.0012588774131101954 

The drift for TSLA 's daily return distribution is: 0.0025460683429589593

In [161]:
#setting up simulation trials
stdev = sigma_tesla**(1/2)
days = 100
trials = 1000
Z = norm.ppf(np.random.rand(days, trials)) #days, trials
daily_returns = np.exp(drift_tesla + stdev* Z)

#calculating price simulation trials
price_paths = np.zeros_like(daily_returns)
price_paths[0] = data["Adj Close"][-1]
for t in range(1, days):
    price_paths[t] = price_paths[t-1]*daily_returns[t]

price_paths = pd.DataFrame(price_paths)
price_paths

In [186]:
import numpy as np
from scipy.stats import gaussian_kde

# Create KDE for the simulated prices
kde = gaussian_kde(final_price)

# Evaluate the cumulative probability at a specific price
x_value = 500 
cdf_value = kde.integrate_box_1d(-np.inf, x_value)  # P(X <= x_value)
prob_above = 1 - cdf_value  # P(X > x_value)

print(f"Smoothed Probability P(X <= {x_value}): {cdf_value:.4f}")
print(f"Smoothed Probability P(X > {x_value}): {prob_above:.4f}")

Smoothed Probability P(X <= 500): 0.6147
Smoothed Probability P(X > 500): 0.3853
In [193]:
muprice_tesla = np.mean(final_price)

sigma2price_tesla = np.var(final_price)

sigmaprice_tesla = np.sqrt(sigma2price_tesla)

n = len(final_price)

standard_error = sigmaprice_tesla / np.sqrt(n)

print(muprice_tesla, sigma2price_tesla, sigmaprice_tesla, n, standard_error)

alpha = .05

lower_bound = np.percentile(final_price, alpha / 2 * 100)
upper_bound = np.percentile(final_price, (1 - alpha / 2) * 100)


print("The 95% confidence interval for Tesla's stock price is (", lower_bound, upper_bound,")")

muprice_F = np.mean(final_price)

sigma2price_F = np.var(final_price)

sigmaprice_F = np.sqrt(sigma2price_F)

n = len(final_price)

standard_error = sigmaprice_F / np.sqrt(n)

print(muprice_F, sigma2price_F, sigmaprice_F, n, standard_error)

alpha = .05

lower_bound = np.percentile(final_price, alpha / 2 * 100)
upper_bound = np.percentile(final_price, (1 - alpha / 2) * 100)
